<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910125-0035</DOCNO><DOCID>910125-0035.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Centerior Energy Corp.:   Ohio Agency Cuts Boosts   In Two Utility Units' Rates</HL><DATE>01/25/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C11</SO><CO>   CX</CO><IN>ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)</IN><LP>   The Ohio Public Utilities Commission said it cut ascheduled 6% rate increase to 2.74% for Toledo Edison Co. andto 4.35% for Cleveland Electric Illuminating Co. Theincreases take effect next Friday.   A spokesman at Centerior Energy Corp., the Cleveland-basedparent of the two utilities, said the reduced rate increasesare in line with needs, after cost-cutting measures weretaken.</LP><TEXT>   The 6% scheduled increase was a result of a settlementapproved by the state in January 1989. Afterward, the statecommission conducted an audit and determined that theutilities could save more than $98 million in operating andmaintenance costs. Half of the savings were applied towardthe scheduled rate increases, the commission said.   The state said the bill for a typical Toledo Edisoncustomer using 750 kilowatthours, now $88.73 a month duringthe winter, will rise to $90.68. The typical ClevelandElectric customer now pays $81.32, which will increase to$84.89.</TEXT></DOC>